[1]
Date: Thu 20 Feb 2003
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@derwent.co.uk>
Source: Oakland Tribune, Thu 20 Feb 2003 [edited]
<http://www.oaklandtribune.com/Stories/0,1413,82~1865~1189583,00.html>

USA (California): Viral Gastroenteritis Outbreaks at Nursing Homes
-------------------------------------------------
A virus causing symptoms similar to those of norovirus infection has
affected at least 600 people around Alameda County, including many elderly
and frail people in at least 13 nursing homes. County health officials
haven't confirmed that the sickness, which causes uncontrollable diarrhea
and vomiting for 24 to 48 hours, is caused by norovirus, which sickened
hundreds of cruise ship passengers last year. But whatever virus it is, it
has put health officials, firefighters, and nursing home administrators on
alert.
Since 6 Jan 2003, viral gastroenteritis has been found at nursing homes in
Alameda, Oakland, Livermore, Pleasanton, and Fremont. The number of cases
in each home has varied. At the Water's Edge Nursing Home in Alameda, at
least 50 percent of the 100 residents have been ill at one time or another
since Wed 5 Feb 2003, said director of nursing Darnelle Zimmerman. "No one
remembers seeing this many cases in Alameda County before," said Sherri
Willis with the Alameda County Public Health Department.
To stop the spread of the virus at nursing homes across the county,
residents are taking meals in their rooms instead of in the communal dining
room, social activities have been curtailed, and signs outside the homes
warn visitors of the virus. Staff members are required to wear gloves and
gowns in facilities grappling with the infection. The county has banned
staff from a facility with an outbreak from visiting or working in
unaffected nursing homes. In Alameda, a handful of firefighters who have
treated and transported sick patients are now sick themselves, Diaz said.
Fire officials have ordered all Alameda firefighters to use a bleach
solution to sterilize rig steering wheels, station counter-tops, floors,
hand-held radios, and anything touched by a crew member called to one of
the 3 facilities where residents are sick. "We are taking extra
precautions," Diaz said. "It can knock an emergency services department out
easily." Nursing homes are using a heavy-duty bacteria-killing chemical for
cleaning.
[Byline: Kristin Bender and Suzanne Bohan]
