[2]
Date: Thu 20 Feb 2003
From: Pablo Nart <p.nart@virgin.net>
Source Vancouver Sun, Wed 19 Feb 2003 [edited)
<http://www.canada.com/vancouver/news/story.asp?id=A56FDD25-D350-4B53-B4A0-7E729184B2FB>

Canada (Surrey): Many Schools Affected by Norovirus Outbreak
--------------------------------------------------
Surrey school officials have been scrambling to contain an extraordinary
outbreak of norovirus infection that has hit students in 15 to 20 schools.
Dale Versfelt, Health and Safety Manager for the Surrey school district,
said although no schools have been closed, activities were restricted in 10
schools as of Tuesday morning. By afternoon, that number had fallen to 4
but was fluctuating so much that Versfelt declined to name the schools. "I
don't want to create a panic," he said, adding that by today the
restrictions on those 4 schools might be lifted and there could be others
in place.
Surrey district dispatches a cleaning squad to scrub down schools whenever
absenteeism exceeds 10 per cent or when 3 or more students are away ill
from any one class, Versfelt said, adding: "It's got me working full-time
just trying to coordinate activities to keep control."
In schools where absenteeism is high, sports teams aren't allowed to play
against other schools, students aren't permitted to work in cafeterias, and
outside groups aren't allowed to use the schools after hours. Versfelt is
asking parents to advise schools if their children have symptoms so that
school and health officials will have a better idea about the prevalence of
disease. Some student absences are a result of parents keeping their
children home in the hope they won't get sick.
Don Bower, spokesman for Fraser Health Authority, said the incidence of
illness linked to norovirus infection is 4 times higher than in previous
years. "There's a lot of norovirus in the community ... it's an unusually
unnerving year," he said. But he doesn't think Surrey has been hit harder
than other municipalities. "We have seen it in the Tri-Cities area and
there has been some in the [Fraser] Valley. I don't think it's unique to
Surrey at all."
Recently 3 Langley elementary schools were scrubbed down after a
significant number of students were away with norovirus infection symptoms,
district spokesman Craig Spence said. But the cleaning seems to have
worked, he said, adding: "It hasn't got out of hand."
Coquitlam school district asked parents to keep children away from Como
Lake Middle School last Friday after 270 of the 550 children were away
Thursday with the illness. On Friday, only 3 children showed up and one
went home ill before the end of the day, said assistant superintendent
Julie Pearce.
[Byline: Janet Steffenhagen]
